KI wird den digitalen Raum nicht demokratisieren – sie wird ihn effizienter privatisieren. (- JD Koehler)


Artificial Intelligence and the Missing Public Square

Draft by JD Koehler

“Artificial intelligence will not democratize the digital world. It will make its privatization more efficient.”

⸻

Artificial intelligence is widely described as a turning point — a technology that will reshape economies, redefine governance and perhaps even renew democratic life. The scale of expectation is striking. So is the assumption behind it: that A.I., by virtue of its sophistication, will correct the structural deficiencies of the digital age.

That assumption deserves scrutiny.

Before asking what artificial intelligence will do to society, we should ask a more basic question: What kind of space is it entering?

A.I. does not arrive in a vacuum. It is layered onto a digital infrastructure that has evolved over decades, shaped less by democratic intent than by market incentives. The architecture of this world — the spaces where communication, visibility and interaction take place — is overwhelmingly private, fragmented and optimized for extraction rather than participation.

If that is true, then the conclusion is difficult to avoid: A.I. will not democratize the digital realm. It will make its existing structure more efficient.

⸻

For years, the debate about digitalization has focused on the interface between state and citizen: how services can be digitized, processes streamlined and access improved. These are legitimate concerns. But they address only one dimension of democratic life.

Democracy does not begin with institutions. It begins with everyday interaction — with the repeated, often mundane encounters through which trust is formed.

These interactions are not procedural. They are spatial.

They depend on environments that allow people to see one another, reach one another and respond to one another without friction or precondition.

In the physical world, such environments are ubiquitous: streets, squares, parks, markets. They are not efficient. They are not optimized. They are not owned by actors whose primary obligation is profit. They are simply accessible.

They are public.

The digital world has no equivalent.

⸻

What exists instead is a system that resembles public space in function but not in structure: a constellation of privately owned platforms that host communication while controlling its conditions.

Access is mediated.
Visibility is allocated.
Interaction is measured, analyzed and monetized.

People still meet. But they do not meet as citizens in a shared space. They meet as users inside proprietary systems.

This distinction matters.

⸻

Its consequences become visible not in grand political crises, but in ordinary moments.

A lost phone cannot reliably find its owner.
A local business cannot reliably reach its customers.
A simple request for help cannot reliably reach a community that would respond.

In each case, communication exists. But it is incomplete, fragmented, contingent on platform logic.

These are small failures. But they point to a larger absence.

There is no digital space that is universally accessible, not privately governed and not structurally optimized for extraction.

There is no digital public square.

⸻

It is into this environment that artificial intelligence is now being introduced.

The prevailing narrative suggests that A.I. will improve the system: better information, better decisions, better outcomes. In principle, that is possible.

In practice, A.I. does not alter the logic of the system it enters. It refines it.

It improves targeting.
It sharpens prediction.
It increases efficiency.

In a platform-driven environment, this means optimizing attention, behavior and monetization with greater precision than before.

The result is not transformation, but intensification.

Artificial intelligence does not replace the current model. It perfects it.

⸻

This is not a flaw of the technology. It is a function of its context.

A.I. amplifies existing structures. It does not redesign them.

If those structures are aligned with public value, A.I. can strengthen democratic life. If they are aligned with extraction, it will deepen that logic.

At present, the digital environment is overwhelmingly oriented toward the latter.

⸻

Democracy depends on more than procedures. It depends on trust — not as an abstract ideal, but as a lived experience.

Trust emerges from repetition: from small, everyday interactions in which people encounter one another as equals and learn, over time, that cooperation is possible.

These interactions require space.

Space that is open enough to allow encounter, stable enough to sustain continuity and neutral enough to avoid systematic distortion.

In their absence, trust becomes harder to form. Social connections fragment. Visibility becomes uneven. Collective understanding erodes.

Political theory has long described this dynamic in terms of social capital. Without it, democratic institutions may persist, but they lose resilience.

The digital world, as currently structured, does little to generate it.

⸻

Much of the discussion about digital democracy focuses on formal participation: online voting, civic platforms, new mechanisms of engagement.

These efforts address the moment of decision.

They do not address what comes before it.

They assume the existence of a shared space in which citizens can encounter one another as equals.

That assumption is increasingly untenable.

Without such a space, participation becomes procedural rather than relational. It may produce outcomes, but it does not sustain the conditions under which democratic life can endure.

⸻

The question, then, is not primarily technological.

It is architectural.

Do we intend to build a digital environment that includes genuinely public space?

Space that is not contingent on platform ownership.
Space that does not require payment for visibility.
Space in which individuals are not primarily treated as data points.

If democracy were designed today, it is difficult to imagine that such spaces would be omitted.

And yet, in the digital world, they are.

⸻

Artificial intelligence will not correct this omission.

It will operate within it.

By increasing the efficiency and scale of existing systems, it may make their consequences more pronounced and more difficult to reverse.

The future of democracy will not be determined by how intelligent our systems become.

It will be determined by the spaces in which they operate.

And for now, those spaces remain overwhelmingly private.

At present, that space remains, in the digital realm, overwhelmingly private.
